### Feed ID Discovery (Prefer Dynamic Over Hardcoded)

**Option A — Pyth MCP** (if `pyth` MCP server is configured in IDE):
- `get_symbols(query="ETH", asset_type="crypto")` → discover feeds interactively
- `get_latest_price(symbols=["Crypto.ETH/USD"])` → verify prices (needs Pro token)
- MCP endpoint: `https://mcp.pyth.network/mcp` (Streamable HTTP, no auth needed)

**Option B — Hermes API** (always available, no setup):
- Fetch ALL feeds: `GET https://hermes.pyth.network/v2/price_feeds`
- Filter: `?asset_type=crypto` or `?query=btc`
- Each feed returns `{ id, attributes: { symbol, asset_type, base, quote_currency } }`

**Option C — Hardcoded** (for known feeds):
- BTC/USD: `0xe62df6c8...415b43`
- ETH/USD: `0xff61491a...fd0ace`
- SOL/USD: `0xef0d8b6f...b56d`

### Hermes (Off-Chain)
- REST: `GET https://hermes.pyth.network/v2/updates/price/latest?ids[]=<feedId>`
- SSE: `GET https://hermes.pyth.network/v2/updates/price/stream?ids[]=<feedId>`
- Feed catalog: `GET https://hermes.pyth.network/v2/price_feeds`
- SDK: `new HermesClient("https://hermes.pyth.network")`

## Pyth MCP Server (Optional)
If the user has the Pyth MCP server configured (`https://mcp.pyth.network/mcp`), leverage it:
- Use `get_symbols` to discover feeds instead of hardcoding IDs
- Use `get_latest_price` to verify price data during development
- Use `get_candlestick_data` for historical/chart data
- **MCP is complementary** — actual on-chain code (contracts, Hermes clients) is still needed
- See `references/mcp-integration.md` for setup across all IDEs

